A Natural Look into our AI-Driven World: An Image Classification Lookthrough

AI is changing the world as we know it. Companies look to train models based on recurring patterns, and visuals such as images make for great training material to help them identify and improve upon their ability to predict patterns and accuracy. For this project, we will be using Tensorflow. Tensorflow is an ML package from Google that enables analysts and engineers to develop everything from Simple Neural Networks to Image Classification. We're gonna focus on the latter, so we will concentrate on using Keras.

The dataset used: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/puneet6060/intel-image-classification

Let's start by loading in the packages we'll need for today.¶

In [27]:
def load_data():
    datasets = ['/Users/noelmccann/Downloads/NLM_Python/Intel/intel-image-classification/seg_train/seg_train', 
                '/Users/noelmccann/Downloads/NLM_Python/Intel/intel-image-classification/seg_test/seg_test']
    output = []
    
    # Iterate through training and test sets
    for dataset in datasets:
        
        images = []
        labels = []
        
        print("Loading {}".format(dataset))
        
        # Iterate through each folder corresponding to a category
        for folder in os.listdir(dataset):
            label = class_names_label[folder]
            
            # Iterate through each image
            for file in tqdm(os.listdir(os.path.join(dataset, folder))):
                
                # Identifying an image's path
                img_path = os.path.join(os.path.join(dataset, folder), file)
                
                # Resizing the image
                image = cv2.imread(img_path)
                image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
                image = cv2.resize(image, img_size) 
                
                # Append the image and its corresponding label to the output
                images.append(image)
                labels.append(label)
                
        images = np.array(images, dtype = 'float32')
        labels = np.array(labels, dtype = 'int32')   
        
        output.append((images, labels))

    return output

In [34]:
AUTOTUNE = tf.data.AUTOTUNE  #prompts tf.data runtime to tune the value dynamically at runtime

train_ds = train_ds.cache().shuffle(1000).prefetch(buffer_size=AUTOTUNE)
test_ds = test_ds.cache().prefetch(buffer_size=AUTOTUNE)

Layers used for this Sequential function:

  • Conv2D: The features which will be extracted from the image (The amount of filters of size x by x).
  • MaxPooling2D: The images get half sized.
  • Flatten: Transforms the format of the images from a 2d-array to a 1d-array.
  • Relu : Returns max(x, 0) if given a value x.
  • Softmax: 6 neurons, probability that the image belongs to one of the classes.
In [35]:
num_classes = len(class_names)

model = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (150, 150, 3)), 
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation = 'relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
    tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(128, activation=tf.nn.relu),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(6, activation=tf.nn.softmax)
])
In [36]:
model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'sparse_categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

With over 5 million trainable paramaters, we are ready to take a crack at fitting the model. We will use 16 epochs, or testing iterations, and a validation split of 20% of total images for this run.

plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)

plt.plot(epochs_range, val_loss, label='Validation Loss')
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')
plt.show()

In our first run, the accuracy of the model is 74.8%. Not bad, but this suggests that there are opportunities for improvement, especially when it comes to overfitting in the training sets and addressing the loss in the test sets.

Checking Our Work¶

Things are starting to come together in our quest to classify the natural scenes of the world. But what can we do to ensure we can have even better accuracy for our training and test data? Let's double-check together.

In [ ]:
predictions = model.predict(test_images) # This creates a vector of probabilities
pred_labels = np.argmax(predictions, axis = 1) #This label selects the highest level of probability. This will come in handy soon.

94/94 [==============================] - 14s 141ms/step

With the prediction labels set up, let's get our Confusion Matrix going. The lighter the color, the more likely the classifier will have issues with identifying the correct image.

In [ ]:
df_cm = confusion_matrix(test_labels, pred_labels)
ax = plt.axes()
sn.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True, cmap="Greens_r", 
           annot_kws={"size": 10}, 
           xticklabels=class_names, 
           yticklabels=class_names, ax = ax)
ax.set_title('Natural World Confusion Matrix')
plt.show()

Glacier and Sea images are the most common pairing when it comes to mislabelled images in the predicted set of images. Moreover, building images can also confuse the current classifier, a caveat that should be kept in mind when the images are being tested.
